1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Qc7 {Black intends to play ...
e5.} (5... Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3) 6. e5 $1 {White knows the correct strategy!}
(6. Nbd2 {also leads to a good version of some well-known positions.} e5 7. a4
a5 8. Nc4 f6 9. O-O Ne7 10. Nh4) ({The computer even shows} 6. Qd2 e5 7. Qc3 {
with good play for White.}) ({How not to play with the white pieces:} 6. Nc3 e5
7. O-O Ne7 8. Re1 Ng6) 6... Bg4 {Even though Black can activate his bishop,
White retains the advantage.} (6... e6 {would lead to a horrible position:} 7.
O-O Ne7 8. Bf4 Nd5 9. Bg3 Be7 10. c4 Nb6 11. Nc3 $18 {[%csl Rc8]}) 7. Bf4 $1 {
This is best, but 7.Nbd2 is also good!} (7. Nbd2 $1 e6 8. h3 Bh5 9. O-O Ne7 10.
Re1 (10. Ne4 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qxe5 $2 12. Bf4 $18) 10... Nd5 11. Nf1 Be7 12. Ng3
Bg6 13. Qe2 (13. Ne4) 13... O-O 14. Ne4 $14) 7... e6 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. h3 Bf5 10.
O-O Nd5 {The knight is not stable on d5, while the d2-knight can enter on d6
via c4.} 11. Bg3 Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Ne4 {Our plan is that our opponent does
not have a plan!} Rad8 (13... Bxe4 14. Qxe4 $16 (14. dxe4 $5)) 14. Nfd2 {
Intending Nc4-d6.} b5 {Preventing White's plan but weakening the structure.}
15. Nd6 $16 Bxd6 16. exd6 Qb6 17. Ne4 a5 18. c4 Nb4 19. a3 Na6 20. Rac1 f6 21.
Rfd1 e5 22. Qe3 b4 23. f4 exf4 24. Qxf4 Bg6 25. a4 Nb8 26. d4 cxd4 27. c5 Qa6
28. Rxd4 Nd7 29. Qf1 Qxf1+ 30. Kxf1 Rfe8 31. Nd2 Re3 32. Bf2 Re5 33. Nb3 Ra8
34. Bg3 Re4 35. Rxe4 Bxe4 36. Nd4 Rc8 37. Bf2 Bd3+ 38. Kg1 Be4 39. Re1 f5 40.
Nb3 Kf7 41. Nxa5 Ra8 42. Rxe4 fxe4 43. Nxc6 Rxa4 44. Nd8+ Ke8 45. Ne6 Ra1+ 46.
Kh2 Rb1 47. c6 Ne5 48. Nc5 Rd1 49. c7 1-0

