{Another good example demonstrating the dark square strategy!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 d5 $2 6. e5 $16 (6. Qa4) (6. d3) 6... e6 $2 7.
d4 Bd7 (7... cxd4 8. cxd4 ({We can even consider} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. cxd4 Ba6 {
This bishop may appear active but in realty it's misplaced because White will
attack it with Na4-c5.} 10. Re1 Ne7 {From here the knight is far away from c5.}
11. Nc3 O-O 12. Na4 Qc7 13. Nc5 {Now Black must either protect the bishop with
a piece or return to c8.} Bc8 $16 (13... Bb5 14. a4 Bc4 15. b3 $18) (13... Qb6
14. b3 Rad8 15. Bf4 $16))) 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. dxc5 a5 10. Re1 a4 11. Nbd2 Qa5 12.
b4 axb3 13. Nxb3 $16 {White has good play on the dark squares and an extra
pawn to boot.} Qc7 14. Bf4 Ne7 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Bh6 Nf5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. g4 Nh6
19. h3 d4 20. Nfxd4 Bd5 21. Rac1 Ra4 22. Re3 Rfa8 23. Rc2 Ng8 24. Nb5 Qc6 25.
Nd6 Bxb3 26. axb3 Ra1+ 27. Rc1 Qxc5 28. b4 Qd5 29. Qe1 Ne7 30. Rxa1 Rxa1 31.
Qxa1 Nc6 32. c4 Qd2 33. Rf3 Nd4 34. Rxf7+ Kh6 35. Kg2 Nc2 36. Ne4 Ne3+ 37. Kf3
Qd1+ 38. Qxd1 Nxd1 39. g5+ Kh5 40. Rxh7# 1-0

