1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 a6 (7...
Qc7 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Nbd2 Nxd2 12. Bxd2 a6 13. Bxc6 Qxc6
14. Rc1 Qb6 (14... Qd7 15. Bf4 Qd8 16. Qd2 Bf5) 15. Bc3 Bd7 16. Qd2 {White is
better but this position is also playable for Black.} {Under no circumstances}
e6 $4 {should be played. After this, Black can never play ...f6 in an
effective way.}) 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 c5 13.
dxc5 Nxc5 14. Nb3 Nxb3 15. Qxb3 Be6 16. Nd4 {Again, a kind of dark-square
strategy! However, compared to the examples we already studied, one difference
is in Black's favour: his pawn is still on e7!} Qa5 17. Qe3 Rac8 18. Bd2 Qa4
19. Bc3 $14 Qd7 20. g4 Rce8 21. Rad1 Qc8 22. Kh2 Bd7 23. f4 Kh8 24. Rd2 Rg8 25.
Nb3 Qc4 26. Nc5 Bc6 27. b3 Qb5 28. a4 Qb8 29. b4 Qb6 30. Rb2 Rc8 31. Bd4 Qd8
32. b5 axb5 33. axb5 Be8 34. b6 Bc6 35. b7 Rb8 36. Reb1 Qa5 37. Rb6 1-0

