{A great example of how to punish passive play by Black!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Qc7 $2 {Slow moves like this one should not be played.} (4...
Nge7) 5. c3 {This is the plan if Black does not do anything.} Nf6 6. Re1 $1 d6
(6... a6 7. Bxc6 Qxc6 8. d4 $1 $16 Nxe4 $2 9. Ne5 Qd5 10. c4 $18) {Black has
played the opening very passively and white has a big advantage!} 7. d4 $16
cxd4 8. cxd4 Bd7 (8... d5 9. e5 ({Since Black has lost too much time, opening
the position also makes sense:} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3) 9... Ne4
10. Nbd2 (10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bd7) 10... Nxd2 11. Bxd2 Be7 12. Bd3 $5 O-O 13.
Qc2 (13. Rc1 Qb6 14. Bc3 Bd7 15. Bb1 Rac8 16. Qd3 g6 17. Qe3) 13... g6 ({After
} 13... h6 {White will slowly switch the queen and bishop battery:} 14. Rac1
Bd7 15. Qd1 {[%cal Yd3b1,Yd1c2]} (15. Bc3)) 14. Bb5 $5 {After having provoked
the weakness ...g6, White returns to the dark-square strategy.} Bd7 15. Bxc6
Qxc6 16. Qd3 Rac8 17. Bc3 Qc4 18. Qe3 $16 {[%cal Ye3h6,Yf3g5]}) 9. Nc3 (9. d5
$5 {Maybe this was even better! Follow the analysis to see some typical ideas!}
Ne5 (9... exd5 10. exd5+ Ne7 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Nc3 g6 13. Bg5 Bg7 14. Qd4 $18
{Black loses material.}) 10. Nd4 $16) 9... Be7 ({If Black plays} 9... a6 {
we can play} 10. Bxc6 {and try to open up the position:} Bxc6 (10... bxc6 11.
e5 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Ne4 Be7 14. Bg5 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ye4d6]}) 11.
d5 Bd7 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Bg5 Be7 14. e5 (14. Rc1 Qb6 15. e5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 $18)
14... dxe5 15. Nxe5 $18) 10. Bf4 (10. d5 $1 $16 Ne5 11. Nxe5 (11. Bxd7+ Nexd7
12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Nb5 $18 (13. Nd4 Nc5 14. b4 Na6 15. Qb3 e5 16. Ne6 $18) 13...
Qb6 14. a4 $18) 11... dxe5 12. dxe6 fxe6 13. Be3 $16) 10... O-O 11. d5 (11. Rc1
Nh5 12. Be3 Nf6 13. h3) 11... Ne5 $2 12. Bxe5 $1 dxe5 13. Bxd7 Nxd7 14. d6 $3 {
and Black resigned because of} Bxd6 (14... Qxd6 15. Qxd6 Bxd6 16. Rad1 $18) 15.
Nb5 $18 1-0

