1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nf6 $6 {This gives White the chance to
take on c6 under favourable circumstances.} (4... Nge7 $1) 5. Bxc6 (5. Re1 {
is another logical continuation.} {If} Qc7 {(not doing anything) then} 6. c3 {
with the idea of preparing d4 is strong. For example} d5 7. e5 Nd7 8. d4 Be7 9.
Bd3 O-O 10. Qc2 g6 11. Qe2 b6 12. Bh6 Re8 13. Bb5 $5 {followed by exchanging
one of Black's knights - the dark-square strategy! We are already familiar
with this from other variations.}) 5... bxc6 (5... dxc6 6. d3) 6. d3 d5 {
After this, Black will end up with a very bad bishop on c8.} ({If} 6... d6 {
with the idea of playing ...e5, then} 7. e5 $1 $16 ({or} 7. c3 {with the idea
to prepare d3-d4 against ...e5.} e5 8. Re1 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11.
Qxd4 O-O 12. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Yc1f4,Ya1d1]})) 7. Nbd2 Be7 8. c4 {A blockading
move in the style of the Nimzo-Indian.} O-O 9. Re1 Re8 10. Qe2 Bf8 {Now, Black
may be threatening ...e5 - now it is time for} 11. e5 $1 $16 (11. Nf1 e5) 11...
Nd7 {Here, Black's only hope is to activate his game with ...f6 - so we
overprotect e5, not allowing Black to free his position. If possible, we would
like to have our pawn on f4.} 12. Nf1 Ba6 13. Ng3 Rb8 14. b3 {[%csl Ra6]} f6
15. Bb2 f5 16. Bc1 $5 Be7 ({If} 16... h6 {we will most likely play} 17. h4 Be7
18. h5 {Our long-term plan is to play g4.}) 17. Qd2 g6 18. Qh6 Bf8 19. Qg5 Be7
20. Qh6 Bf8 21. Qh3 Bg7 22. Bh6 {White keeps solid control of the dark squares
on the kingside. It's important to never allow ...h6-g5. During the whole game
the bishop on a6 remains a spectator.} Qe7 23. Rad1 Rf8 24. Bg5 Qe8 25. Bf4 Qd8
26. Nf1 Qe7 27. N1d2 Rfe8 28. Nb1 {[%cal Yb1c3,Yc3a4]} Nf8 29. Nc3 Qf7 30. Ng5
1-0

