{White demonstrates a good strategy against the doubled c-pawns - resembling a
reversed Nimzo!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6 5. b3 d5 $2 {
This is already a mistake - Black should try to push ...e5 instead.} 6. d3 Nf6
({The ending after} 6... dxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {is very bad for Black.} c4
(8... Ne7 9. c4 $16 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6]}) 9. Nbd2 (9. bxc4 Ba6 10. Nfd2 $14) 9...
cxb3 10. axb3 $16) 7. Qe2 Ba6 8. c4 {Of course! Black's light-squared bishop
can never enter the game.} d4 9. e5 $1 ({If instead, we allow something like} 
9. Nbd2 Nd7 10. O-O e5 {, Black gets a good game. For example} 11. Re1 Bd6 12.
Nf1 O-O 13. Ng3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. h3 f6 16. Rad1 Nf8) 9... Nd7 10. Bg5 Be7 11.
Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O h6 13. Nbd2 $16 f5 {Now Black threatens to play ...g5.
That's why White changes plans:} 14. exf6 $3 gxf6 15. Rae1 e5 16. Nh4 $18 {
White has opened the position - this is heavily in his favour since Black is
playing without his a6-bishop.} Qh7 17. Qh5+ Qf7 18. Qf3 Bb7 19. Ne4 Qe6 20.
Qh5+ Kd8 21. f4 Kc7 22. fxe5 fxe5 23. Nxc5 Nxc5 24. Rxe5 Qd6 25. Rxc5 Rhf8 26.
Rcf5 Rxf5 27. Nxf5 Qe5 28. Qxh6 Kb6 29. Qf4 Qxf4 30. Rxf4 Rf8 31. g4 Bc8 32.
Kg2 c5 33. h4 Ka5 34. a3 Be6 35. Kf3 Bxf5 36. Rxf5 Rb8 37. Rxc5+ Ka6 38. b4 Re8
39. g5 Re3+ 40. Kf4 Rxd3 41. g6 Rd1 42. g7 Rf1+ 43. Ke4 Rg1 44. Rg5 1-0

