{A great example of how humans used to beat computers in strategic battles!
This was possible a long time ago!} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. Bxc6 bxc6
5. O-O d5 $2 {The computer mishandles the position.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. e5 Nd7 8. c4
h6 9. Qe2 {Strengthening the control of e5.} Ba6 {(this makes no sense)} 10. b3
Be7 11. Re1 O-O 12. Bb2 Qc7 ({After} 12... d4 {the b2-bishop will soon reenter
the game via c1.}) 13. Nbd2 Rad8 14. Nf1 Rfe8 15. Ng3 Nf8 16. Nh5 $16 Ng6 17.
Bc3 Rd7 18. Qb2 Rb8 19. Qa3 Qb7 20. Ba5 Ra8 21. Rac1 {White wants to provoke
either ...d4 or ...dxc4.} Rf8 {The computer does not find a plan.} 22. h3 Rb8
23. Rc2 Re8 24. Bd2 Red8 25. Be3 Qb6 26. Bd2 Qb7 27. Ba5 Rb8 28. Qc1 Bd8 {
Finally, Black exchanges bishop, which simplifies White's task.} 29. Bxd8 Rbxd8
30. Nf4 Nxf4 31. Qxf4 dxc4 $2 {Finally this concession - the activity down the
d-file does not compensate the worsening of the pawn structure.} 32. dxc4 Qc7
33. Qe3 Qa5 34. Qe2 Rd3 35. Kh2 R8d7 36. Rb1 $1 {White prepares the exchange
of rooks with the following manoeuvre.} R3d5 37. Rbb2 Qc7 38. g3 Qa5 39. Kg2
Rd8 40. Rd2 R5d7 41. Rxd7 Rxd7 42. Rd2 Bc8 43. Rxd7 Bxd7 44. Qd2 $18 {Now
White has a technical winning position.} Qc7 45. Qc3 Bc8 46. Nd2 Qd8 47. Ne4
Qd4 48. Qxd4 cxd4 49. Kf3 f6 50. Nc5 Kf7 51. Ke4 d3 52. Kxd3 fxe5 53. Ke4 Kf6
54. b4 g6 55. a3 g5 56. g4 h5 57. gxh5 Kg7 58. Kxe5 Kh6 59. f4 gxf4 60. Kxf4
Kxh5 61. Ke5 Kh4 62. Kd6 e5 63. Kxe5 Bxh3 64. Kd6 Bf1 65. Kxc6 Kg5 66. Kb7 Kf5
67. Kxa7 Ke5 68. Kb6 Kd4 69. Nb3+ Kc3 70. Na5 Bg2 71. c5 Kb2 72. c6 Kxa3 73. c7
Bh3 74. b5 Ka4 75. Nc6 Bc8 76. Na7 Be6 77. c8=Q Bxc8 78. Nxc8 Kb4 79. Kc6 Kc3
80. b6 Kd4 81. b7 1-0

