1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 a6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 {Compared to
the previous examples, Black's bishop on c8 has an open diagonal. Duda plays
against this bishop in a very instructive way.} 7. h3 Nf6 ({After} 7... Qd3 8.
Re1 {the queen will soon be driven away.}) 8. Re1 O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 {
Black's light-squared bishop appears to be good but it cannot find a good
square.} Nd7 $2 (10... c5 $5 {was probably best.} 11. d5 b5 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Bf4
c4 14. Be5 e6 {with some counterplay.}) (10... Bd7 11. Nc3 Rc8 12. Bf4 Re8 13.
Qc2 $16) (10... b6 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Bf4 c5 13. dxc5 (13. d5 $16) 13... bxc5 14.
Qc2 $14 {Black's pair of bishops is a factor but the weakness of the c5-pawn
is even more important.}) (10... b6 11. Nc3 a5 12. Bf4 Ba6 13. Qc2 Nd7 14. Rad1
$16 {Black's bishop does nothing on a6! For the moment White hasn't a clear
plan - this depends on what Black will do.}) 11. Nc3 b5 (11... e5 {After this
White has some options though I would not exchange on e5, speeding up Black's
development.} 12. Be3 (12. d5 $5) 12... exd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 $16) 12.
Bg5 Bb7 13. Qd2 c5 14. d5 $16 Nb6 15. Rad1 (15. Bh6 $5 Nc4 16. Qc1 $16 Bxh6 17.
Qxh6 Nxb2 $4 18. Ng5 $18) 15... Rc8 16. Bh6 Qc7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. b3 {White
has a strategically winning position since the b7-bishop is very bad.} Rcd8 (
18... c4 19. b4 $1 {and Black does not get any activity while White now has
the d4-square for his pieces. The c4-pawn is securely blockaded.}) 19. Qg5 h6
20. Qe3 Rfe8 21. Rd2 b4 22. Ne2 e6 23. Rc1 exd5 24. Rxc5 Qe7 25. Nfd4 Qxe4 26.
Qg3 Qe5 27. Qxe5+ Rxe5 28. Nc2 Rc8 29. Rxc8 Nxc8 30. Nxb4 a5 31. Nd3 Re7 32.
Nc5 Nb6 33. f3 a4 34. Kf2 axb3 35. axb3 Bc8 36. Ra2 Rc7 37. Ra5 Nd7 38. Nd3 Rc2
39. Rxd5 Ra2 40. Ke3 Nf6 41. Re5 Be6 42. Ndc1 Rb2 43. g4 Nd5+ 44. Kf2 Nf4 45.
Kg3 Nxe2+ 46. Rxe2 Rb1 47. Rc2 Bxb3 48. Nxb3 Rxb3 49. Rd2 g5 50. Rc2 Kg6 51.
Rc6+ f6 52. Ra6 Rc3 53. Rb6 Ra3 54. Rc6 Rb3 55. Rd6 Ra3 56. Rc6 Rb3 57. Rd6 Ra3
1/2-1/2

