1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 (7. e5 {
is playable but the downside is that Black will soon attack e5 with ...d6.} Nd5
8. d3 d6 9. Bxc6 bxc6 $132 {Playing e5 has created a target.}) 7... Qc7 8. d4 (
8. d3 $5 e5 9. a3 (9. Nbd2) (9. Bg5 Qb6) 9... a6 10. Bc4 d6 11. b4 b5 12. Bb3
Bb7 13. Be3 Nd7 14. Nbd2) 8... cxd4 9. cxd4 a6 (9... e6 {Not a good move - I
just want to make a point:} 10. Nc3 d5 11. e5 Nd7 12. Bf4 a6 13. Bxc6 {Since
Black has played ...g6 and ...e6 White can play for a dark-square strategy.})
10. Bxc6 {This is good but it has nothing to do with the dark-square strategy 
(see 9...e6). White's play is based on his space advantage and the fact that
Black's bishop on c8 cannot find a suitable square.} bxc6 (10... dxc6 11. Nc3
b6 (11... c5 12. e5 $18) (11... Nd7 12. Be3 (12. Bg5 e5 13. d5 $16) 12... e5
13. Rc1 exd4 14. Bxd4 $16) 12. Bg5 a5 (12... Be6 {This is not a stable square
for the bishop.} 13. Qc2 Rad8 14. Rad1 $16) 13. e5 (13. Rc1) (13. Qd2)) 11. Nc3
d6 (11... d5 12. e5 Nd7 (12... Ne8 13. Na4 $18) 13. Bf4 $3 (13. Na4 $16 c5 14.
dxc5 Nxc5 15. Qxd5 $18) 13... e6 (13... Nb6 14. Rc1 $16) 14. Na4 Rb8 (14... c5
15. dxc5 Nxc5 (15... f6 16. exf6) 16. Rc1) 15. Rc1 $16) 12. Bf4 (12. Bg5 h6 (
12... Rb8 13. Qd2 h6 14. Bxh6 Bxh6 15. Qxh6 Rxb2 16. Ng5 e5 17. dxe5 dxe5 18.
Re3)) 12... Nh5 ({If} 12... Bb7 {then for example} 13. Rc1 (13. Qd2) 13... Nd7
14. Qd2 e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Bxe5 dxe5 18. Na4 $16 {with a big,
risk-free advantage for White.}) 13. Bh2 Rb8 14. e5 $16 {[%cal Yg2g4]} f5 15.
exf6 Rxf6 16. Qe2 Rb7 17. Ne4 Rf8 18. Nc5 Ra7 19. Ng5 Qb6 20. Qc4+ d5 21. Qc3
Bf6 22. Nf3 Ng7 23. Ne5 Nf5 24. Rad1 Nd6 25. b3 Rc7 26. Ng4 Bg5 27. Be5 Bf4 28.
Bxf4 Rxf4 29. Qg3 Bxg4 30. hxg4 Rf7 31. Re6 Qa5 32. Re2 Nb5 33. Rc2 Nd6 34. Qe5
Qb6 35. Rd3 Rc8 36. Rf3 Rxf3 37. gxf3 Qa7 38. Re2 Rf8 39. Kg2 Rf7 40. Rc2 a5
41. Rc1 Qb6 42. Qe6 Kg7 43. Qe3 Kg8 44. Nd7 Qd8 45. Ne5 Rf6 46. Nxc6 Qd7 47.
Nxe7+ 1-0

