1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 a6 8. Bxc6
dxc6 (8... bxc6 {Here we don't want to play e4-e5:} 9. e5 $6 (9. d4 $1 $14)
9... Nd5 10. c4 Nb6 11. d3 d6 $132) 9. d3 ({After} 9. d4 $5 {Black has only
one way to get counterplay:} cxd4 10. cxd4 c5 $1 11. d5 b5 $132) 9... Qc7 (9...
Bd7 10. Be3 (10. e5 {Here, this move is not effective as the knight has the
square c7 available:} Nd5 11. c4 Nc7 12. Nc3 Ne6) 10... b6 11. Nbd2 Qc7 12. d4
$1 cxd4 13. cxd4 Rad8 14. Rc1 Qb7 15. Qc2) 10. e5 $1 {This move is justified as
} Nd5 {can be met strongly with} (10... Nd7 11. Bf4 $16) 11. c4 $1 {when the
knight has to move to an inferior square.} Nb6 (11... Nb4 $2 12. a3 $18) 12.
Nc3 $16 {White's d-pawn isn't weak since Black's pieces are too passively
placed to exploit it.} Rd8 13. Qe2 Bf5 14. Rd1 Qd7 (14... Nd7 15. g4 Be6 16.
Bf4) 15. Ne1 Qc7 16. Bf4 {White has defended d3 and Black is left without a
plan. During the next moves White will improve his position and consolidate
his advantage.} Nd7 17. Nf3 Nf8 18. Bh2 Qd7 19. Na4 $1 Bxd3 20. Qe3 Qf5 21. Nb6
Bc2 22. Rd2 Rxd2 23. Qxd2 Re8 24. Ne1 Be4 25. f3 Bxe5 26. Bxe5 Qxe5 27. fxe4
Qxe4 28. Nf3 e5 29. Nd7 Nxd7 30. Qxd7 Qe3+ 31. Kh1 Re6 32. Rf1 Rf6 33. Re1 Qf4
34. Qe8+ Kg7 35. Qxe5 Qxc4 36. Rd1 h6 37. Nh2 h5 38. Nf3 Qxa2 39. Ng5 Qa4 40.
Rd7 1-0

