{A great example in the Rossolimo with ...g6 main line! Black was left without
any play and felt compelled to complicate matters with a sacrifice!} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. d4 d5 8. e5 Ne4 9. Bxc6
bxc6 10. Be3 cxd4 (10... Qb6 11. Qc1 Rb8 12. b3 Qa5 13. dxc5 Rxb3 14. axb3 Qxa1
15. b4 Qa4 16. Nbd2 $16 Nxd2 17. Bxd2 Bd7 18. Bh6 $18) (10... c4 11. b3 Ba6 12.
Qc2 (12. Nfd2)) 11. cxd4 Qb6 12. Qc1 a5 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 {Here we see the
semi-dark-square strategy in action: Black's pawn is not on e6 - which would
be very bad for him - yet still White has some advantage.} Bf5 (14... e6 15. b3
Bd7 16. Bc1 $5 {[%cal Yc1a3,Ya3c5]} (16. Rac1) 16... Rfc8 17. Ba3 Bf8 18. Bc5 (
18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Rac1 $18) 18... Bxc5 19. dxc5 Qb7 20. Nd4 Rcb8 21. a3 $18 {
White is strategically winning. With a3 White has ruled out ...b4. Next, he is
going to exploit Black's weaknesses on the dark squares.}) 15. b3 Rfb8 (15...
a4 16. b4 $3 a3 17. Nh4 Bd7 18. Rab1 Rfb8 19. Rb3 Bf8 20. Bd2 (20. h3 e6 21.
Reb1) 20... e6 21. Nf3 $16) 16. Nd2 (16. h3 $3 a4 17. g4 Bd7 (17... Be4 18. Nd2
axb3 19. axb3) 18. Reb1 axb3 19. Rxb3 Qa6 20. Rxb8+ Rxb8 21. a4 h5 22. gxh5
gxh5 23. Kh2 Qe2 24. Nd2 $16) 16... h5 (16... a4 $1 $132) 17. h3 (17. a3 $1 $16
{would have prevented any counterplay connected to ...a4. White went for a3
only later.} a4 $140 18. b4) 17... Rc8 (17... a4 $1 $132) 18. Rac1 Bf8 19. a3
Rab8 20. Qb2 Qd8 21. Rc3 Qd7 22. Rec1 f6 23. Rc5 Rb5 24. a4 Rxc5 25. Rxc5 Bxh3
26. gxh3 Qxh3 27. Nf1 fxe5 28. dxe5 Bg7 29. Qd4 Qe6 30. Rxa5 Bxe5 31. Qh4 Rf8
32. Ra7 Bd6 33. b4 Rf3 34. Ra8+ Kf7 35. Bh6 Qe2 36. Rf8+ Ke6 37. Rxf3 Qxf3 38.
Be3 Kd7 39. a5 Kc8 40. Bc5 Bf4 41. Qxe7 Qg4+ 42. Ng3 Bxg3 43. fxg3 Qxg3+ 44.
Kf1 Qd3+ 45. Kf2 Qd2+ 46. Kf3 Qd1+ 47. Kf4 Qg4+ 48. Ke5 Qe4+ 49. Kf6 Qxe7+ 50.
Kxe7 h4 51. Kd6 h3 52. Bg1 d4 53. Kxc6 d3 54. a6 Kb8 55. b5 d2 56. a7+ Ka8 57.
b6 1-0

