1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {In this lecture we are going to cover 3...Nf6 and
some more rarely played lines. White can get the advantage against 3...Qc7, 3..
.Qb6, and 3...a6. Even in the best continuation of this chapter, 3...Nf6,
Black must follow very narrow path to get a playable position.} Nf6 4. Bxc6 {
This is my recommendation for this repertoire. White gets good chances for an
advantage, while there's considerably less theory to know compared to the main
line 4.Nc3. You are familiar with many strategies against the doubled c-pawns
from our first two lectures.} dxc6 (4... bxc6 5. e5 $16) 5. d3 Qc7 {This is
Black's best chance - with the idea of playing ...e5. We prevent this by
playing} 6. e5 $1 Nd5 7. c4 $1 {when Black's knight will end up being
misplaced after both 7...Nb6 and 7...Nb4.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "ROSSOLIMO 3...Nf6, 3...Qc7"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[EventDate "2024.12.01"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {This is a completely playable move.} (3... Qc7
{is a playable yet slightly dubious continuation - Black neglects his
development and loses time with his queen. We answer it with typical Rossolimo
play.} 4. O-O {If Black plays something passive our basic plan consists of
playing c3 and d4.} Nf6 $5 (4... e5 5. c3 Nf6 6. d4 $16 {Black is lagging in
development so White should try to open the position as fast as possible.}) (
4... e6 5. c3 $16 (5. Re1 $1 $16) 5... a6 6. Bxc6 Qxc6 (6... dxc6 7. d4) 7. Re1
$16 {Next comes d4 with a strong initiative for White.}) (4... a6 5. Bxc6 dxc6
(5... Qxc6 $2 6. d4 $1 $16 {This is a very bad version of an Open Sicilian for
Black, as he has lost several tempi, and he is about to lose some more! I like
6.d4 best although White has at least two other good moves:} (6. Re1 d6 (6...
e6 7. d4) 7. d4 $16) (6. Nc3 d6 7. d4 $16) 6... Qxe4 7. Nc3 Qc6 8. d5 Qc7 9. d6
$1 Qxd6 10. Qxd6 exd6 11. Nd5 Kd8 12. Ng5 $16 (12. Bd2 $16)) (5... bxc6 6. c3
$1 ({I don't like} 6. d3 {because of} e5) 6... d6 (6... e5 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4
exd4 9. Qxd4 d6 10. Bf4 Bg4 11. Nbd2 $18 {Black has many weaknesses and is too
far behind in development.}) 7. h3 {We prepare d4 without allowing ...Bg4.} ({
But since Black has lost too much time} 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 Bg4 {should also be
very good for White.} 9. Bf4 $16) 7... Nf6 8. Re1 e5 (8... g6 9. d4 cxd4 10.
cxd4 Bg7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Bf4 $16) 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 Be7 12. Nc3
O-O 13. Bf4 $16) 6. d4 $3 {Breaking the rules for once! Usually, we would play
e5 (preventing ...e5). But 6.d4, opening the position, is justified since
Black lost time with ...a6 and ...Qc7.} (6. a4 $1 {is an interesting and
strong alternative.} a5 ({Black would like to play} 6... e5 {but then} 7. a5 {
fixes the queenside. For example} Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. d3 Bd6 10. Nbd2 Nf6 11. Re1
O-O 12. g4 (12. Nf1) (12. Nc4 {is also possible.} h6 {Now we can unpin the
knight with} 13. Qe2 Rad8 14. Qe3 Nd7 15. Bd2) 12... Bg6 13. Nc4 $16) 7. d4
cxd4 8. Qxd4 Bg4 9. Nbd2 $16 (9. Qe5 Qxe5 10. Nxe5 Be6 11. Be3 Nf6 12. Nd2 $16)
9... e6 10. Qe5 $3 $16 (10. Nc4 $3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nf6 12. Be3 $16)) 6... cxd4 7.
Qxd4 Bg4 (7... c5 8. Qe5 $3 $14 (8. Qe3 $14) 8... Qxe5 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. Nc3 Be6
11. Be3 Rc8 12. a4 b6 13. Rfd1 $16 g6 14. Nd5 $3 Bxd5 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5) 15.
exd5 Bg7 16. Nc4) 8. Ne5 $1 (8. Qe5 $5 Qxe5 9. Nxe5 Be6 10. Nc3 f6 11. Nd3 $16
{Even in the endgame White's advantage in development is felt.}) (8. Nbd2 e6 (
8... Nf6 9. e5 Rd8 10. Qf4 Bxf3 11. Nxf3 Nd5 12. Qe4 $16 {Centralising the
queen (this is good whenever it is possible!) - from e4 the queen controls the
whole board.}) 9. Qe5 $14) 8... Rd8 9. Qc3 Nf6 10. f3 Be6 11. Nd3 $3 g6 12. Bf4
$14) 5. Re1 a6 $6 (5... d6 6. c3 a6 7. Bxc6+ Qxc6 8. d4 $16 (8. e5 $16 {
Even this move is good now - though I generally dislike this. But here, White
gets a strong initiative. For example} dxe5 9. Nxe5 Qd6 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 e6
12. Bf4 Qd8 13. Nc3 Be7 14. Re3 O-O 15. Rg3 $16) 8... cxd4 (8... Nxe4 9. d5) 9.
cxd4 d5 10. Ne5 Qb6 11. Nc3 dxe4 12. Qa4+ Nd7 13. Bf4) 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. e5 $3 {
ALWAYS THIS! We never allow Black to play ...e7-e5!} (7. d3 e5 8. a4 a5 9. Nbd2
Be7 10. Nc4 Nd7) 7... Nd5 8. d3 {As a rule, we will kick the knight with c4
when Black cannot play ...Nb4!} Bg4 (8... Bf5 9. Nh4 {We chase away the bishop
in order to continue with c4:} Be6 10. c4 Nb6 (10... Nb4 $2 11. a3 $18) 11. Nc3
O-O-O 12. Qe2 $16) 9. c4 $3 $16 Bxf3 (9... Nb4 10. a3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $18) 10.
Qxf3 (10. gxf3 $16 {Even this is good for White.} Nb6 11. Bd2 $3 Nd7 12. e6 $16
) 10... Nb4 11. e6 (11. Qe2 $18 O-O-O 12. Rd1 Qd7 13. Nc3 Nxd3 14. e6 fxe6 15.
Be3 $18 e5 16. Ne4 Qf5 17. f3 Nf4 18. Rxd8+ Kxd8 19. Rd1+ Ke8 20. Qd2) 11...
fxe6 12. Bf4 Qd7 13. Nc3 Nc2 14. Be5 Nxa1 15. Rxa1 $18 {This is +5 for White!})
(3... a6 $6 {This is played surprisingly often, though it can be regarded as a
loss of time.} 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d3 Bg4 (5... Qc7 6. e5 (6. Qd2 $5 {is an
amazing computer suggestion.}) 6... Bg4 7. Bf4 e6 8. Nbd2 Ne7 9. h3 Bh5 10. Bh2
(10. Qe2)) 6. h3 Bxf3 (6... Bh5 7. Qe2) 7. Qxf3 $16) (3... Qb6 4. Nc3 a6 5.
Bxc6 Qxc6 6. d4 $16 {Now we get an Open Sicilian with several extra tempi for
White. The pair of bishops cannot compensate for White's massive lead in
development.}) 4. Bxc6 $5 {This move is excellent! We are fighting for the
advantage without having to know much theory! In general, we don't take on c6..
.only when it's a specific theoretical line (as is the case here). REMEMBER
TWO THINGS: 1) We do not allow Black to play e7-e5 - we play e5 ourselves! 2)
When we play e4-e5, WE MUST MAKE SURE that in case of 1.e5 Nd5, we will very
soon be able to play c2-c4, without Black being able to play ...Nb4 after
c2-c4!} ({We must avoid} 4. d3 $6 Qa5+ $1 5. Nc3 Nd4 $1 6. Bc4 b5 $1 {with
good counterplay for Black.} 7. Bd5 $2 (7. Bb3 Nxb3 8. cxb3 e6 9. Bg5 Bb7 $132)
7... Nxd5 8. exd5 b4 9. Ne4 b3+ $17 {1/2-1/2 (45) Nguyen,N-Pavlidis,A/Berlin
GER 2015}) (4. Qe2 $6 e5 $3 $132) (4. Nc3 {This is the main move with lots of
theory!}) 4... dxc6 (4... bxc6 5. e5 $1 (5. d3 $5 d6 6. e5) 5... Nd5 6. d3 e6
7. O-O Be7 8. c4 Nc7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Ne4 {If} f6 {then} 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bh6
Rf7 (12... Re8 13. Ne5 $18) 13. Ng3 $16 {Black has a big pawn centre, but his
king is very weak now!}) 5. d3 $1 (5. e5 $6 Nd5 6. d3 Bf5 $1 {Now we cannot
play c2-c4 because of the replay ...Nb4. Don't forget rule Number 2 : when we
play 1.e5 Nd5, we must make sure that we can follow up with a very fast c2-c4!}
7. O-O (7. Nh4 e6 8. Nxf5 exf5 $132) 7... e6 $132) (5. Qe2 $6 e5 $3 $11) 5...
Qc7 {This is best - with the idea of playing ...e5.} (5... Bg4 $6 6. h3 (6.
Nbd2 e6 7. h3) 6... Bh5 {All we need to know is that we will soon play g4,
with a strong initiative!} (6... Bxf3 7. Qxf3 {We don't mind Black playing ...
e5 when he has exchanged his light-squared bishop.} e6 (7... g6 8. O-O Bg7 9.
a4 a5 10. Be3 b6 11. Nd2 Nd7 12. Rab1 O-O 13. Qg3 e5 14. f4 $16 exf4 15. Bxf4)
(7... e5 8. O-O Be7 (8... Bd6 9. Bg5) 9. a4 O-O 10. Na3 Nd7 11. Qg3 b6 12. Nc4
$16 (12. f4 exf4 13. Bxf4 $16)) {Now any logical move will give White a
significant advantage!} 8. O-O Be7 9. Qg3 (9. a4 O-O 10. Nd2 $16) 9... O-O 10.
e5 $16) 7. Qe2 (7. g4 Bg6 8. Nbd2 $16) 7... e6 8. Nbd2 Nd7 9. g4 Bg6 10. b3 $16
{Black has a very problematic bishop on g6. White can improve his position and
may be going for castling queenside. For example} (10. Nc4) 10... a5 11. a4 $1
Be7 12. Bb2 f6 13. Nc4 e5 14. Nh4 Bf7 15. Nf5 $16) (5... Nd7 6. Bf4 $1 $14 {
Not allowing Black to play ...e5.} (6. e5 $1 $14) 6... e6 (6... Qb6 7. b3 (7.
Nbd2 $5 Qxb2 8. O-O $16)) 7. e5 $16 (7. Nbd2 Be7 8. h4 $16) 7... Be7 (7... Nb6
8. c4 $1 {Now both the bishop on c8 and the knight on b6 are very poorly
placed.} Be7 9. h4 (9. Nc3 O-O 10. Qe2 (10. h4))) 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Ne4 $16) 6. e5
$1 {We prevent Black's plan.} (6. O-O $6 e5 7. Nbd2 Be6 $5 {The idea is ...
Be6-h6-Nd7.} (7... b5 $1 8. a4 Be7 $1 (8... Bd6 $5 9. Nh4 g6 10. Re1 O-O 11.
Nf1 Nh5 12. Nf5) 9. Re1 O-O 10. Nf1 Be6 11. Ng3 Rfe8 12. Ng5 Bd7 $36 13. Nf5
Bf8 14. Qf3 c4 $5 15. dxc4 bxc4 16. Bd2 Rab8 $17) 8. b3 h6 9. Bb2 Nd7 10. Nh4 (
10. Nc4 f6 11. Nh4 g5 12. Nf5 O-O-O 13. Qf3 h5 $132) 10... O-O-O 11. a3 Kb8 12.
Bc3 g6 {1/2-1/2 (29) Bruzon Batista,L-Pavlidis,A/Berlin GER 2015} (12... Rg8
13. b4 Nb6 $17 14. bxc5 Na4)) (6. Nbd2 $6 e5 $1 7. Nc4 $2 b5 $3 8. Ncxe5 $2 (8.
Ne3 Bd6 9. Nh4 g6 10. Qf3 Be7 $132) 8... Bd6 9. Bf4 Nh5 $19 10. g3 f6 $19) 6...
Nd5 7. c4 $1 {THE ONLY GOOD MOVE! Otherwise, Black plays ...Bf5! followed by ..
.Nb4.} (7. h3 $6 Bf5 {Now, we can no longer play c4.} 8. b3 (8. a3 h6 9. g4 (9.
Qe2 e6 10. O-O (10. Nbd2 Nf4) 10... O-O-O 11. Nbd2 g5 12. Ne4 g4 $17) 9... Bh7
10. e6 O-O-O $17) 8... e6 9. Bd2 O-O-O 10. Nc3 h6 $36 {0-1 (38) Markidis,
K-Pavlidis,A/Porto Rio Hotel 2015}) 7... Nb6 (7... Nb4 8. a3 Na6 9. O-O $1 {
Black will get some activity by attacking the d3-pawn, but White can handle it.
At the end of the day, Black's a6 knight will have a hard time finding a good
square. For example} Bf5 (9... Bg4 10. Re1 O-O-O 11. Nc3 $14 Qd7 (11... e6 12.
Ne4 h6 13. Bf4 $16 f5 14. Nd6+) 12. h3 $1 Bh5 (12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 e6 14. Bg5
$18 Be7 15. Ne4) 13. e6 $3 fxe6 14. g4 Bg6 15. Ne5 Qd4 (15... Qc7 16. Bf4 $18)
16. Qf3 $18 Be8 17. Re4 Qd6 18. Bf4) 10. Qe2 O-O-O 11. Rd1 $14 Bg4 (11... Qd7
12. d4 (12. Nc3)) 12. Nbd2 e6 13. h3 Bh5 14. Ne4 $16) 8. Nc3 {Now Black can
try to put pressure against e5 or d3, i.e. to play ...Bg4 or ...Bf5.} (8. h3 $2
Bf5 9. b3 O-O-O $17) 8... Bg4 (8... Bf5 9. Qe2 O-O-O 10. Ne4 $14 e6 (10... f6
11. Bd2 $1) 11. Bg5 $1 Re8 (11... Be7 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nd6+ Kb8 14. O-O-O $16
(14. Qe3 $16) 14... Nc8 15. Nxf5) 12. h3 Nd7 13. Ng3 $14) 9. Bf4 Qd7 $1 ({If} 
9... e6 {we are clearly better after} 10. h3 Bf5 11. Qe2 O-O-O 12. Ne4 Bxe4 13.
Qxe4 Qd7 14. Rd1 {due to Black's misplaced knight on b6.} (14. O-O-O)) 10. Qe2
$1 (10. Ne4 Nxc4 $1 11. dxc4 Qf5 12. Nxc5 Qxf4 $132) 10... O-O-O 11. O-O-O Qf5
12. Qe3 Bxf3 13. gxf3 $1 $14 (13. Qxf3 Nd7 14. Qe4 Qxe4 15. Nxe4 $14 {White
has a very nice plus in the endgame!} h6 16. h4 g6 17. Bg3 Bg7 18. f4) 13... e6
14. Ne2 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Ge4][%cal Ye2g3,Yg3e4]} *

