1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 {This is an interesting and entirely playable
variation for Black.} (3... Nd4 4. Nxd4 cxd4 5. O-O ({But not} 5. d3 $4 Qa5+
$19) 5... a6 (5... e6 6. d3 Ne7 7. Nd2 a6 8. Ba4 b5 9. Bb3 Nc6 10. a4 Bb7 11.
f4 $16 (11. Qh5 g6 12. Qh3 $14)) 6. Ba4 e6 {This position could also be
reached after 3...e6 4.0-0 Nd4. White has a nice advantage - for example:} 7.
d3 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. f4 (9. c3 Bc5 10. Nd2 (10. Qg4 $5) 10... Ne7 11. Qh5)) 4.
O-O ({A playable alternative is} 4. Bxc6 bxc6 {but Black gets his
counterchances.}) (4. c3 {is another reasonable move, after which Black should
play} d5 5. exd5 Qxd5 ({After} 5... exd5 6. d4 {we get our repertoire against
2...e6!})) 4... Nge7 {This is essentially Black's only good move!} (4... d6 $2
{A very passive move!} 5. c3 $1 (5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4) 5... Bd7 (5... a6 6. Bxc6+
bxc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rc8]}) 6. d4 $16) (4... g6 $2 5. c3 Bg7
6. d4 $16 {For example} cxd4 7. cxd4 d5 8. Bxc6+ {(before Black can play ...
Nge7)} bxc6 9. e5 {with a strategically winning position.}) (4... Nf6 $2 5.
Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 $16 {[%csl Rc8] We will eventually play e5 whenever Black is
ready to play ...e5 himself.}) (4... a6 $2 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. d3 Nf6 7. Nbd2 $16 {
In this structure Black suffers due to his passive bishop on c8.}) (4... Qc7 $2
5. c3 $16 {[%cal Yd2d4]}) (4... Qb6 $2 5. Bxc6 $5 {looks very interesting
since after} (5. Nc3 {is also very logical}) 5... Qxc6 (5... bxc6 6. d3 d6 7.
e5 $1 $16) 6. d4 $5 {White gets a huge lead in development.} ({Or} 6. Re1 {
[%cal Yd2d4]})) (4... Nd4 5. Nxd4 cxd4 6. d3 {Simplest, in my opinion - see 3..
.Nd4.} ({Or} 6. c3 a6 7. Bd3 $14)) 5. d4 $1 {This is the most simple
continuation for White to get a slight edge. We play an Open Sicilian only
after Black put his knight on e7!} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {Now, one of our plans is to
set up a Maroczy Bind with c2-c4 (after retreating the bishop).} Qb6 (6... Ng6
7. Be2 $1 {We retreat with the bishop in order to prepare c4.} ({Or} 7. Be3 Be7
8. Be2 O-O 9. c4 d6 10. Nc3 $14) 7... Be7 (7... Bc5 {see MODEL GAME 0-1 (48)
Caruana,F (2839)-Nakamura,H (2767) London 2014}) 8. c4 O-O 9. Nc3 b6 10. Be3
$14 Bb7 11. Nb3 $14 (11. Nc2 $14)) (6... a6 {see MODEL GAME 1-0 (27) Safarli,E
(2676)-Tersinsev,A (2194) Batumi 2018}) (6... d6 7. Be3 (7. Be2) 7... a6 8. Be2
Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nc6 10. Qd2 Be7 11. c4 O-O 12. Nc3 b6 13. Rfd1 $16 Ne5 (13... Bb7
$2 14. Na4 $18) 14. f4 Nd7 15. Rac1 Qc7 (15... Bb7 $2 16. e5 $18) 16. Bf3 $16)
7. Nxc6 bxc6 {This is best in my opinion.} (7... dxc6 8. Bc4 $1 {With this
move, White anticipates ...e6-e5!} Ng6 9. a4 $1 {This is a very useful move,
gaining space on the queenside. Note that in this structure we do not put our
knight on c3!} (9. Kh1 {is another interesting move played by Caruana. See
MODEL GAME 1-0 (45) Caruana,F (2807)-Lenic,L (2646) Tbilisi 2017}) 9... Be7 {
Now, we have several good moves - so memorising lines is not necessary!} (9...
a5 10. Nd2 Be7 (10... e5 $2 11. Bb3 $16 (11. Qh5 $16)) 11. Qh5 O-O 12. Nf3 $14
({White can also prepare Nc4 with} 12. Bd3 $5 e5 (12... Nf4 13. Nc4 $1 Qc7 14.
Bxf4 Qxf4 15. e5 g6 16. Qe2 $16) 13. Nc4 Qc7 14. Be3 Ra6 (14... Nf4 15. Qxe5)
15. g3 $16)) 10. Kh1 $5 (10. c3 $1 O-O 11. Be3 $1 Qc7 (11... Qxb2 $4 12. Ra2)
12. Nd2 $14 e5 13. g3 $1 {REMEMBER THE RULE: when we see ...e6-e5 with a
knight on g6, we go g3! to keep it out of play!} Bh3 14. Re1 Rad8 15. a5 $16 (
15. Qh5 Qc8 16. Be2 Be6 17. Nc4 $16)) (10. Qe2 O-O 11. Bb3 e5 12. Be3 Qc7 13.
g3 Bh3 14. Rd1 $14) 10... O-O 11. f4 $14) (7... Qxb5 $2 8. Nd4 Qb6 (8... Qc5 9.
Be3 $16) (8... Qe5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Be3 $16) 9. Nc3 (9. c4 Nc6 10. Nb5 $16) 9...
Ng6 10. Be3 $16) (7... Nxc6 8. Be2 {We retreat the bishop, intending c4.} (8.
Bd3 {is also possible.} d6 9. c4 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Rb1 a6 12. Be3 Qd8 (12...
Qc7 13. Rc1) 13. Rc1 Ne5 14. Be2 $16 {[%cal Yf2f4]}) 8... Be7 (8... Bc5 9. Nc3
{[%cal Yc3a4]} Qc7 10. Na4 Be7 11. c4 $14) 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 {White has a good
version of a Maroczy Bind. For example} d6 11. Rb1 {(protecting b2, intending
Be3)} a6 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Yc3d5]} Qb8 14. Na4 $18) 8. Bd3 $14 (8.
Be2 $14 Ng6 9. c4 Be7 (9... Bc5 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Na4 $16) 10. Be3 $1 c5 (10...
Qxb2 11. Bd4 Qb4 12. Bxg7 Rg8 13. Bc3 Qb8 14. Nd2 Nf4 15. g3 $16) 11. Qd2 (11.
Qc2 $5 Bb7 12. Nc3 O-O 13. f4 d6 14. b4 $14 Qc7 (14... a6 15. a3) 15. b5) 11...
O-O 12. Nc3 d6 (12... Bb7 13. f4 (13. b4) 13... Bc6 (13... f5 14. Qxd7) 14.
Rad1 $14 (14. g3 $14)) 13. Rad1 Bb7 14. f4 $14 (14. b4 $5 $14)) 8... Ng6 (8...
d5 9. Qe2) 9. c4 Be7 (9... Bc5 {runs into} 10. Nc3 {threatening Na4.} Qc7 11.
Na4 Be7 (11... Bd4 12. c5 O-O 13. Re1 (13. Qc2 d6 14. cxd6 Qxd6 15. Be3 $1 Bxe3
16. fxe3 $14) 13... d6 14. cxd6 Qxd6 15. Be3 e5 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Rc1 $14 Ne5
18. Nc5) 12. c5 $1 $16 {Fixing the structure. Sooner or later Black will have
to move his d-pawn, which leads to pawn weaknesses. For example} d5 (12... O-O
13. Be3 d5 14. cxd6 Bxd6 15. g3 e5 16. Qc2 Bh3 17. Rfd1) 13. cxd6 Bxd6 14. g3)
10. Nc3 O-O (10... c5 11. f4 O-O 12. Qh5 $40 {[%cal Yf1f3]}) 11. Rb1 $1 (11.
Na4 $5 Qc7 12. c5 {see MODEL GAME 1-0 (27) Caruana,F (2811)-Lenic,L (2662)
Chess.com INT 2018}) 11... c5 (11... Rd8 12. Be3 Qc7 13. Qd2 $14) (11... Qc7 {
see MODEL GAME 1-0 (45) Caruana,F (2779)-Gelfand,B (2764) Elancourt 2013}) 12.
Be3 Qc6 (12... Qc7 13. f4 $1 $16 ({After} 13. g3 $2 {the knight can relocate
itself to c6:} Ne5 $1 $132) 13... Bb7 (13... e5 14. Nd5) 14. Qh5) (12... Bb7
13. b4 Qc7 14. b5 $16) 13. Qh5 $16 (13. f4 Bb7 14. Qe2 $14) 13... Bb7 14. f4
$16 *

