if Black plays for example} 5... a6 6. Ba4 Qc7 {Here we have at least two good
ways to play:} 7. c3 (7. d3 b5 8. Bb3 Bb7 9. c3 $1 $16 (9. Nd2 e6 10. f4 (10.
Nf3 Bc5 11. c3 dxc3 12. bxc3)) (9. f4 e6 10. f5)) 7... dxc3 8. Nxc3 e6 9. d4
$16) 6. d3 Bc5 7. Qh5 (7. Qg4 $1 {would have been strongest, immediately
highlighting the drawback of playing ...Bc5.} Nf6 (7... g6 8. Qg3 $16 (8. Qe2
a6 (8... Qa5 9. Bc4) 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bb3 Bb7 11. Nd2 (11. c3)) (8. Nd2 $16)) 8.
Qxg7 (8. Qg3 $5 $14) 8... Rg8 9. Qh6 $16) 7... Qb6 8. Ba4 Nf6 9. Qh4 $14 {
White has a comfortable advantage.} O-O 10. Nd2 d5 11. e5 Nd7 12. Nf3 $16 Qd8
13. Bg5 f6 14. exf6 gxf6 15. Bh6 Rf7 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Nb6 18. Bb3 e5 19.
Qh4 Be6 20. f4 exf4 21. Rae1 Bf5 22. Rxf4 Bg6 23. Ref1 f5 24. Qg3 a5 25. a4 Qd7
26. Rh4 Re8 27. Be3 Nc8 28. Bd4 Re6 29. c4 Ne7 30. cxd5 Nxd5 31. Qf3 Rd6 32.
Be5 1-0

