1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 7. Nxc6 bxc6
8. Bd3 Ng6 9. c4 Be7 10. Nc3 d6 11. Rb1 O-O 12. b4 Bf6 13. Be3 Qc7 14. Qd2 a5
15. b5 Bxc3 16. Qxc3 cxb5 17. Rxb5 $16 {Ideally, White would like to take with
the c-pawn (when he would be strategically winning), but even taking with the
rook offers a stable advantage. White's dark-squared bishop is quite strong.}
Ne5 18. Be2 Bd7 19. Rb2 Rfc8 20. Rc1 Bc6 21. f3 Rab8 22. c5 {Opening the
position for the pair of bishops.} Rxb2 23. Qxb2 d5 (23... dxc5 24. Rxc5 Nd7
25. Rc1 $18 {leads to a technically winning position. Black's remaining bishop
is restricted by White's pawns.}) 24. exd5 exd5 25. Bd4 f6 26. Qb6 Nd7 27. Qxc7
Rxc7 28. Rb1 {White does not have a decisive advantage yet, but he won due to
his superior endgame technique.} Kf7 29. f4 Rb7 30. Rb3 Rb4 31. Rxb4 axb4 32.
Kf2 Ba4 33. Ke3 g6 34. g4 f5 35. gxf5 gxf5 36. Ba6 Ke6 37. Bc8 Bc6 38. Be5 Ke7
39. Kd4 Kd8 40. Ba6 Nf8 41. Bd6 Ng6 42. Bd3 Nh4 43. Be2 Ng6 44. Bf3 Kd7 45.
Bxd5 Nh4 46. Bxc6+ Kxc6 47. Ke5 Nf3+ 48. Kxf5 Nxh2 49. Kg5 Kd5 50. Kh6 Nf3 51.
Kxh7 Nh4 52. Kh6 Ke6 53. Kh5 Nf5 54. Kg5 Nd4 55. Kg6 Nf5 56. Be5 Ne7+ 57. Kg5
Nc6 58. Bg7 Ne7 59. Bf8 Nf5 60. c6 Nd4 61. c7 Kd7 62. Bd6 Ne6+ 63. Kg6 Nd4 64.
f5 Nc6 65. f6 1-0

