1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e6 4. O-O Nge7 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qb6 7. Nxc6 dxc6
8. Bd3 (8. Bc4 $1) 8... e5 (8... Ng6 {In the structure with ...dxc6 we will
NOT play} 9. c4 $4 {since it would just create a weakness on d4. Instead, we
can play} (9. a4) ({or} 9. Nd2) 9... e5 $15) 9. Be3 Qc7 (9... Qxb2 10. Nd2 $44
{looks too risky for Black.}) 10. Nd2 Ng6 11. a4 Be7 ({If} 11... Be6 {we can
exchange Black's good bishop with} 12. Bc4 {, for example:} Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Be7
14. a5 O-O 15. g3 $14 {The pawn structure is symmetrical yet Black's position
is horrible. White's pieces are much better and the pawn on a5 is also quite
annoying.}) 12. Qh5 {The queen is very strong on h5. This is a consquence of
having the knight developed to e7.} O-O 13. Bc4 (13. g3 $5 Be6 14. Bc4 Bxc4 15.
Nxc4 $14) 13... Nf4 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Nf3 $14 h6 16. Rad1 b5 17. axb5 cxb5 18.
Bd5 Bb7 19. Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Rd5 a6 21. Ne5 Rad8 22. Rfd1 Bf6 23. Nd7 Rxd7 24.
Rxd7 Qxe4 25. c3 b4 26. Qf3 Qxf3 27. gxf3 bxc3 28. bxc3 Bxc3 29. Rc7 Bb4 30.
Ra7 a5 31. h4 g6 32. h5 g5 33. Rdd7 Kg7 34. Kg2 Kf6 35. Rdb7 Ke5 36. Ra6 f6 37.
Rh7 Kd4 38. Rxh6 f5 39. Rhg6 g4 40. fxg4 fxg4 41. Rxg4 Kc4 42. h6 Kb5 43. Ra7
Rh8 44. h7 a4 45. Rg8 Rxh7 46. Rxh7 a3 47. Rb7+ Kc4 48. Ra8 Kb3 49. Kf3 1-0

