1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {In this lecture we cover the topical line} e5 {
White can fight for a small advantage with} 4. O-O Bd6 $1 {This non-standard
move is Black's best chance. After other continuations White usually gets the
advantage by simply going c3 followed by d4.} 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 b5 7. Bb3 $5 {
- This will be analysed in some detail in the theory section.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "ROSSOLIMO 3...e5"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B30"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[EventDate "2024.12.01"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 e5 {This is an interesting and topical line, but we
definitely can pose some problems!} 4. O-O $1 ({We cannot win a pawn by playing
} 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nxe5 $2 Qd4 $15 (5... Qg5)) 4... Bd6 {This is Black's idea
in this line.} (4... Qc7 $2 {does not pose any problems. We continue with the
standard} 5. c3 $16 {followed by d4.}) (4... d6 $2 5. c3 a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. d4
$16) 5. c3 $1 ({Let me show you what NOT do to as White:} 5. d3 Nge7 6. Re1 O-O
7. Nbd2 Bc7 8. c3 a6 9. Ba4 b5 10. Bc2 d6 {White has played to passively and
Black has a good game and can continue with ...f5.}) 5... a6 (5... Nf6 $2 6. d4
$16 {Black is almost lost after this!}) (5... Nge7 $6 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4
8. Nxd4 O-O (8... Qc7 9. Nf3 a6 10. Be2 $16) 9. Nc3 $14) 6. Ba4 (6. Bc4 {
is less precise for tactical reasons:} Nf6 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 exd4 $1 9. e5
Bxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. Re1 O-O $1 12. Rxe5 Qc7 $1 $11 {and Black regains the
piece with equal chances.}) 6... b5 (6... Nge7 $2 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 exd4 9.
Nxd4 {White has a clear advantage, for example} O-O 10. Nc3 Be5 11. Be3 $16) (
6... Qc7 {A tricky move - if we would play d4, then h2 would be hanging in the
end.} 7. d3 {I like this move best! After} (7. Bb3 $5) (7. Re1 $5) 7... Nf6 {
White has the strong} 8. Nh4 $1 g6 9. Bh6 $16) 7. Bb3 $1 {Provoking ...c5-c4 -
the good thing about this line is that we can get this position practically by
force!} c4 (7... Nf6 $2 8. d4 c4 9. Bc2 $16) (7... Qc7 $2 8. d4 $1 cxd4 9. cxd4
exd4 10. e5 $1 $16) 8. Bc2 Nf6 9. d4 (9. d3 {leads to the same thing.} cxd3 10.
Qxd3) 9... cxd3 10. Qxd3 Bc7 $5 {This is best - Black can now recapture with
his queen on f6 after Bg5-Bxf6.} (10... Be7 $6 11. Bg5 {After Bg5 we want take
on f6 when Black is forced to take back with the bishop!} Nh5 {Nakamura played
this, nevertheless it's dubious.} (11... O-O 12. Bxf6 $1 {I prefer to
immediately eliminate this knight to prevent a possible ...Nh5. We are
fighting for control of d5 and will exploit Black's weaknesses on the d-file.}
Bxf6 13. Nbd2 d6 14. Rfd1 Be6 15. Bb3 {White has a nice positional advantage.
For example} (15. Nf1) 15... Na5 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. b4 Nc6 18. a4 $16 Rb8 19.
axb5 axb5 {Now White can quietly improve his position with} 20. g3 $5 Qc7 21.
Kg2 $16) (11... d6 12. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 13. Rd1 Be7 14. Bb3 O-O 15. Bd5 Bd7 16.
Nbd2 Rb8 17. Nf1 $16 {The knight is transferred to e3 from where it can go to
d5 and f5. A possible continuation can be} g6 18. Ne3 (18. h4 Kh8 19. Ne3 f5
20. exf5 gxf5 21. Bxc6 Bxc6 22. Nxf5) 18... Kh8 19. b4 f5 20. a4 f4 21. Nc2 $14
) (11... h6 $2 {Very dubious since we were going to take on f6 anyway!} 12.
Bxf6 Bxf6 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Rfd1 Qc7 15. Nf1 Na5 16. Ne3 Nc4 17. Nd5 Qd8 18.
Rab1 $16 {We are forced to defend b2 but will soon get rid of the knight on c4:
} Bb7 19. Nd2 Nb6 20. Bb3) 12. Be3 $1 O-O (12... Qc7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. b4 {
Intending a4 and possibly Bb3.} d6 15. a4 Rb8 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bb3 Kh8 18. Qe2
$5 g6 19. Bh6 Ng7 20. Rfc1 $16) 13. Nbd2 d6 14. a4 Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 Kh8
17. Qe2 (17. Bb3) 17... Nf4 (17... Nf6 18. Bd3) 18. Bxf4 exf4 19. Bb3 $14) (
10... Bc5 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. b4 Bb6 14. a4 Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. Na3
$1 {Since Black has lost some time we are able to directly attack b5.} Na7 17.
Bb3 O-O 18. Nc2 $16) (10... Qc7 {We can use the same plan after this move and
will continue with} 11. Bg5 {Now Black has to defend with} Be7 {anyway.} 12.
Rd1 O-O 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Nbd2 d6 15. Nf1 Rd8 16. Ne3 Ne7 17. Bb3 Be6 18. Rac1
Rac8 19. h4 $16 {followedy by g3 and Kg2, improving the position.}) 11. Rd1 $1
{An interesting waiting move! We wait for Black to castle and will only then
go for Bg5!} ({The immediate} 11. Bg5 $1 {is also good.} h6 12. Bh4 $5 {
This is very ambitious and risky !} ({A solid alternative is} 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13.
b4 O-O 14. a4 bxa4 15. Rxa4 Rb8 16. Nbd2 a5 $5 $132 {The computer assesses
this position as about equal.}) 12... g5 13. Bg3 d6 14. Nbd2 (14. Rd1 $5) (14.
a4 $5 b4 15. Nbd2 $14) 14... Nh5 15. Rfd1 $14) 11... h6 $5 {Stopping Bg5 is
best.} (11... O-O $6 12. Bg5 $16 {Now, after 0-0 its not an easy decision to
go for h6-g5 anymore!} h6 13. Bh4 $1 d6 14. Nbd2 Be6 (14... g5 $2 {is punished
with the typical piece sacrifice} 15. Nxg5 $1 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Kg7 17. Qf3 {
Nf1-e3 is coming up and Black has a hard time of freeing himself. For example}
Rg8 18. h3 Be6 19. Nf1 Kg6 20. Bh4 Rh8 21. Qg3+ Kh7 22. Ne3 $16) 15. Bb3 Qe7
16. Nf1 $16 (16. a4 $16)) (11... d6 $6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. a4 Rb8 (
14... b4 15. Qc4 Bd7 16. cxb4) 15. axb5 axb5 16. Na3 Na7 17. c4 $3 O-O (17...
b4 18. Ba4+) 18. cxb5 $16) 12. Be3 $5 (12. Nbd2 $5 {is also good, with a
slight advantage for White.} O-O 13. Nf1 d6 14. h3 Be6 15. Ng3 Bc4 16. Qd2 Ne7
17. Qe1 $14 {We can continue with Be3 and/or Nh4-f5.}) 12... d6 13. Nbd2 O-O
14. Nf1 Be6 15. Qe2 Qe7 (15... Re8 16. Ng3 Ng4 17. Bb3 $1 $14) 16. Nh4 $1 $14 *

