{[%evp 0,11,11,8,44,44,44,44,45,36,36,14,41,36] In this lesson we are going to
discuss one of the main replies to the Rossolimo by Black, 3... g6!?.} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {Black wants to frianchetto his Bishop. This is one of
the main lines against the Rossolimo.} 4. O-O {The correct moveorder.} Bg7 5.
c3 {Now, Black has two main options. ...e5 and ....Nf6.} e5 {Black wants to
play d6-Ne7, 0-0 and flank attack on the kingside with moves like f5-f4.} (5...
Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 $5 {This line has been covered in this lecture. The game
now transitions into a middlegame where plans matter instead of exact theory.})
6. d3 {The aim is to play Be3-d4 next. Both sides will try to prove their
strategic dominance.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "ROSSOLIMO 3...g6"]
[Black "THEORETICAL OVERVIEW"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[EventDate "2024.12.09"]

{[%evp 0,25,26,8,44,44,44,44,41,35,35,13,30,-8,-8,-7,4,4,4,-10,0,-16,6,6,6,8,7,
-2]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 {One of the main lines of the Rossolimo.
Black's play is very simple he wants to control the center with Bg7, develop
his Knight on f6, and castle short. White's most accurate move order is to go
for short-side castling immediately.} 4. O-O Bg7 {Black's next typical plan is
e5-Nge7-0-0 and to reach a Botvinnik setup. To meet it, we try to plan d4 as
soon as possible. Or Black can also play a combination of Nf6-0-0 and d5.} 5.
c3 {Black now has two main choices: e5 or Nf6.} Nf6 (5... e5 {The other main
line.} 6. d3 $1 {A very intresting idea. White wants to play Be3-d4 and seize
the initiative. Remember we shouldn't quite move after ..d3. This line is full
of tactical and strategic traps for both sides.} (6. d4 {is also completely
playable.} cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4 8. Bf4 a6 $1 {The only move to survive for Black.
The most popular Nge7 is actually a big mistake as you will see in a moment.} (
8... Nge7 $2 {White now has a few ways to get edge.} 9. Bd6 a6 10. Bd3 $1 $16
O-O 11. Nbd2 $1 $16 (11. a4 $1 {gaining space on the queen side.} b6 12. Nbd2
Bb7 13. b4 $16 {White is good.})) 9. Ba4 Nge7 10. Bd6 b5 11. Bb3 Bb7 {Black
now wants to play Nc8, which is a serious threat.} 12. Re1 $3 (12. Nbd2 $2 {
Do not play this impulsive move.} Nc8 $1 $17) 12... Nc8 13. e5 $1 Nxd6 14.
exd6+ Kf8 {Several games have been played from this position, White has two or
three interesting tries! The computer is stuck on the 0.00 evaluation but
practically White scores quite well! (You can always try te 6.d3 line if you
prefer! )}) 6... Nge7 $1 {the only good move for Black.} (6... d6 $2 7. d4 $3
$16 {Black is slow with his development.}) (6... Qb6 $2 7. Na3 Nge7 8. Nc4 $1
$16 Qc7 9. Be3 d6 10. d4 {Once again, Black is not well developed.}) (6... a6
$2 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. a4 $1 {Threatning to end the game with a5.} a5 9. Na3 Qc7
10. Be3 b6 11. d4 $1 $16 {Opening the center as Black's King is in the center.}
) 7. Be3 $1 d6 8. d4 $1 exd4 $1 {again the only move!} (8... cxd4 $2 9. cxd4
O-O 10. d5 $1 $16 {this is like a very good version of the Classical King's
Indian for white, because somehow, the c4-c5-cd6 plan has been executed very
very fast and the queenside is already open.}) 9. cxd4 O-O (9... a6 $2 {
is a concrete mistake.} 10. Bxc6+ Nxc6 11. dxc5 dxc5 (11... Bxb2 {trying to
win an exchange when your King is unsafe is dangerous.} 12. Nbd2 Bxa1 13. Qxa1
O-O 14. Bh6 f6 15. Nc4 $3 $18 {Black is busted with his passive pieces and
many weaknesses.}) 12. Nc3 $3 $16 {simple but so effective.}) (9... Bg4 $6 {
This is another important line and you should know it well.} 10. Nc3 $3 Bxf3 (
10... O-O $2 11. dxc5 dxc5 12. Bxc5 Nd4 13. Bxd4 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 $16 {White is a
pawn up with active pieces.}) 11. gxf3 cxd4 (11... Qb6 12. d5 $3 $16 {wins
material.}) 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 $6 (12... O-O 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qd2 Qd7 15. Rad1 Qh3
16. Be2 Rad8 17. Qg5 $14 {White's next plan would be Kh1-Rg1 and Nd5.}) 13.
Qxd4 O-O 14. Qf6 $14 {The weak d6-pawn and King says it.}) 10. Nc3 Qb6 $1 11.
Bxc6 $1 Nxc6 (11... Qxc6 $6 12. h3 $16 {simply stopping Bg4, it's not clear
where Black will develop his Bishop.}) 12. Rb1 $3 Bg4 $1 (12... cxd4 $2 13. Nd5
Qd8 (13... Qc5 14. b4 Nxb4 15. Ne7+ $1 Kh8 16. Nxd4 $16 {White is better.}) 14.
Nxd4 Re8 15. f3 $16 {harmonious.}) 13. Nd5 Qa5 14. dxc5 dxc5 15. Qb3 $1 Bxf3
16. gxf3 {And this ..is a very difficult position to handle with black! ....he
will make the mistake soon !}) (5... d5 $6 {Quite premature.} 6. d3 $1 (6. e5
$1 {intending d4.} Bg4 (6... Bd7 7. Bxc6 bxc6 {White almost always capture on
c6, destroying Black's coordination.} (7... Bxc6 8. d4 $16 {In a closed
position, pair Bishops are not important.}) 8. d4 $16 cxd4 9. cxd4 {The weak
pawn on c6 stands out.}) 7. d4 Qb6 8. Bxc6+ Qxc6 9. Nbd2 $1 e6 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Nxf3 $16 {White has a huge space advantage.}) (6. Qa4 {this wins a pawn but
black may get some annoying long-term compensation} dxe4 7. Bxc6+ bxc6 8. Qxc6+
Bd7 9. Qxe4 Nf6 10. Qc4 Rc8 $14 {Engines claim this to be slightly better for
White, but practically Black looks good.}) 6... Nf6 7. e5 Nd7 8. d4 $14 {
White has quite a bit space.}) (5... a6 $6 {this a6 move can be played on
various occasions...but white follows a strategy against the Bc8 and gets an
advantage! There is no need to memorize this a6 ...on each move separately...
just the ideas !} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 (6... bxc6 {We should know the plans not the
theory.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 d6 9. h3 {important move! Black has no place for
his Bishop.} Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Re1 a5 12. Bf4 Ba6 13. Qd2 {We place our
pieces in the center and keep pressure. No theory is needed again!}) 7. d3 $1
$14 {planning Be3-d4.} (7. h3 $1 {Also possible. White's plan is d4.} Qd3 8.
Re1 Nf6 9. Re3 Qd8 10. d4 O-O 11. Re1 $14 {We are back.}) 7... e5 {stopping d4
but blocks its own Bishop.} 8. a4 {Threatning a5, which is almost a checkmate
positionally.} a5 9. Na3 Ne7 10. Nc4 Qc7 11. Be3 b6 {Black's Knight on e6 is
very bad.} 12. b4 axb4 13. cxb4 cxb4 14. Bxb6 Qb8 15. Bc5 {White is clearly
better.}) (5... d6 $2 {Quite quick as it allows full central control.} 6. d4
cxd4 7. cxd4 a6 (7... Bd7 8. Nc3 a6 9. Be2 {White has good central dominance.})
8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. h3 Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Re1 $16 d5 12. e5 Nd7 13. Na4 {White
controls everything.}) 6. Re1 (6. d3 $6 {is too passive and slow!}) 6... O-O {
White has now two main lines.} (6... a6 $6 7. Bxc6 dxc6 8. d4 $1 {In such
positions without our knight on c3, we can actually Bg4 as it is met by a
combination of h3-Nd2.} (8. h3 $1 $14 O-O 9. d3 $14 {is very harmonious.}) 8...
cxd4 9. cxd4 Bg4 10. Nbd2 $1 O-O 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Nxf3 $14 Nd7 13. Bg5 {White
has good central control and active pieces.}) 7. h3 $5 {A positional approach.
Black is almost left with ...e5} (7. d4 $1 {Challenging Black immediately.} d5
(7... cxd4 {This will transpose sooner or later to the immediate 8...d5 9.
e5-Ne4} 8. cxd4 d5 9. e5 Ne4 10. Bxc6 {In the past, 10.Nc3!? used to be the
mainline. However, it involves too much study.} bxc6 11. Be3 {stopping c5 and
planning Qc1. Remember, we don't want to play Qc2 as it is met by Bf5 ideas.}
f6 (11... Qa5 $6 12. Nbd2 Bg4 13. Nb3 Qb6 14. h3 Bd7 15. Ng5 $16 {getting
control of the c5-square. White has the edge.}) 12. Nbd2 $14 (12. h3 Qb6 13. b3
a5 14. Nbd2 $14 {White is good.}) 12... fxe5 (12... Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Bg4 14. exf6
exf6 15. Bf4 $3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qd7 17. Kg2 $14 {Black has quite a few
weaknesses.}) 13. Nxe5 $16 {It is tough to deal with the c6-pawn.}) (7... Qb6
$6 {This doesn't look good and White will get the usual Rosolimo- type
advantage !} 8. Bxc6 $1 {the simplest solution.} dxc6 9. h3 cxd4 10. cxd4 Rd8
11. Nc3 $14 Ne8 12. Na4) 8. e5 Ne4 9. Bxc6 $1 bxc6 10. Be3 {Black's position
here is quite problematic, he can play all sorts of different moves and move
orders but White will be able to consolidate the center and prevent pawn
breaks (except for f6, which comes along with weaknesses for black!). In the
end, White keeps the edge.} cxd4 (10... Qb6 11. Qc1 {Remember we always keep
the queen on c1 and not c2 to avoid Bf5.} cxd4 12. cxd4 a5 $1 (12... Rb8 13. b3
$16 {is another transposition}) 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 $14 {White keeps good
control of all pawn breaks by Black and he will gradually expand on the
kingside.}) (10... Rb8 11. Qc1 {transpositions to other lines :} Qb6 (11... f6
12. Nbd2 $1 $16 {Usually, in most cases after f6, We just develop our pieces.
Do note all the captures by Black, lead to an advantage for White. After 1...
fe5 we usually play 2.Nxe5!}) 12. b3 cxd4 (12... Qa5 {Black is trying to make
use of the fact that he hasn't played cxd4, in fact, this position has been
played sometimes, but White is clearly better!} 13. dxc5 $3 $16 {free pawns.}
Rxb3 (13... Nxc5 14. b4 {wins material.}) 14. axb3 Qxa1 15. b4 $1 Qa4 16. Nbd2
$16 {We will soon take over the a-file as well.}) 13. cxd4 $16 {Black is left
without any counterplay. The next plan is Nc3 and slowly maneuvering our
f3-knight to c5.}) 11. cxd4 f6 (11... Qb6 12. Qc1 {transposes to 10...Qb6 11.
Qc1}) (11... a5 12. Qc1 Bd7 13. Nbd2 $14 {After the e4-Knight is traded there
is not much problems for us.}) 12. Nbd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2 Bg4 14. exf6 $1 exf6 15.
Bf4 $3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qd7 17. Kg2 $14 {despite the ugly pawn structure, White
is better. Our king is protecting the weaknesses}) 7... e5 $1 (7... a6 {
Loses a tempo.} 8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. e5 Ne4 12. Be3 $16 {
With an extra tempo compared to the main line with 7.d4} (12. Nc3 $16 Nxc3 13.
bxc3 a5 14. Ba3 {is also possible.})) (7... d5 $2 {This is a very common
mistake by Black, they have mixed up the h3 and d4 lines. The problem is Black
doesn't have Ne4 after the standard e5 push, as it is met by d3 unlike in d4
variation where this works.} 8. e5 Ne8 {Black is now going way too passive.} 9.
d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Bd7 (10... Nc7 {Black can't afford a weakness now.} 11. Bxc6
bxc6 12. Nc3 Ne6 13. Na4 Rb8 14. Ng5 $18 {Black is busted.}) 11. Nc3 Nc7 {
and now, literally every bishop move gives a huge advantage.} (11... e6 $2 {
Blocks its own bishop for no reason.}) 12. Bf1 $16 {White is better, the
alternative Bishop moves were good too.}) (7... Qb6 {is not as bad, as before}
8. Ba4 $5 {We should not capture on c6, now that Black has castled.} (8. a4 $5
{is also quite intresting.}) 8... Rd8 $1 9. d3 d6 10. Bb3 $5 h6 11. Na3 $14 {
White has a good position.}) (7... d6 $2 {fails to control the center.} 8. d4
cxd4 9. cxd4 Bd7 10. Nc3 $16 a6 11. Bxc6 $1 Bxc6 12. d5 Bd7 13. Be3 $16 {
White has quite a bit of space.}) (7... Qc7 $2 {Once again, this move doesn't
actually serve any purpose.} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Be3 Qb6 12.
Bxc6 Qxc6 13. Nfd2 $1 Nxd2 14. Qxd2 Be6 15. Nc3 $14 {White has a small edge
because of the space.}) 8. d3 $1 {This is a very nice way to play without
theory. Our plan is to expand on the queenside with Be3-Nbd2-a3-b4. The
position is of no forced character, so typical ideas matter the most.} (8. d4
$5 {A more concrete approach.} cxd4 9. cxd4 Nxd4 (9... exd4 {is little dubious.
} 10. e5 Nd5 11. Bg5 Qb6 12. Na3 h6 13. Bh4 $14 {Black's pieces are
mis-coordinated.}) 10. Nxd4 exd4 11. Qxd4 d5 12. e5 Ne4 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3
Qc7 15. Bg5 $14 {Next up is Bf6 and threats against the weak King.}) 8... d6 {
If we keep Black's g6 Knight on e7 instead, then White would be in trouble
with ideas like f5.} (8... Re8 9. Be3 $1 {planning d4.} d6 (9... Qb6 $2 10. Na3
a6 11. Nc4 $3 $16 {wins material.}) 10. a3 Bd7 11. b4 a6 12. Bc4 $14 {The game
goes on but White has the upper hand.}) (8... Qc7 {Black stops Bxc6 ideas.} 9.
Be3 d6 10. a3 {typical plan intending b4.} a6 11. Bc4 b5 12. Ba2 Be6 13. Bxe6
fxe6 14. Nbd2 Kh8 15. b4 $16 {Black's structure is messed up.}) 9. a3 Bd7 10.
Be3 a6 11. Bc4 b5 12. Ba2 Qe7 13. b4 {with a rich middlegame ahead.} *

