103,51,85,54,99,98,98,98,98,108,115,54,119,71,71,-44,-1,-47,-51,-48,-7,-24,14,
-8,48,55,71,127,119,112,112,126,126,91,149,170,639,638]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 {...e5 is another good option.} 6. Re1 O-O (6... e6
{makes no sense. This is a non-standard move.} 7. d4 cxd4 8. cxd4 d5 9. e5 Nd7
10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Na4 {Game over for Black.}) 7. h3 e5 8. d3 d6 9.
a3 Bd7 10. b4 {White can also play Be3-Nd2 first, it doesn't matter.} b6 11.
Be3 h6 12. Bc4 Kh7 13. Nbd2 a6 (13... Be6 {Black wants to trade the Bishops to
open up the file for attack on the kingside, while White will try to exploit
the doubled pawns.} 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qb3 Qe7 16. bxc5 (16. d4 exd4 17. cxd4
cxd4 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 {Black has too many weak pawns.}) 16... dxc5 17.
Nc4 {The doubled pawns are scary but White also needs to be careful for his
d3-pawn.}) 14. Nf1 (14. Bb3 {preparing Nc4-d4.} Ng8 15. Nc4 Qc7 16. d4 {
Black will next follow up with ...f5 and it will be a fight.}) 14... Qc8 15.
Ng3 Ra7 16. Ba2 Rc7 17. d4 cxd4 18. cxd4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Ne5 20. Qe2 Qb7 21. f4
Nc6 22. Rad1 Nxd4 23. Bxd4 Ba4 24. Rd2 Bc6 25. f5 Re7 26. Bb1 Ne8 27. Qf2 Bxd4
28. Rxd4 Rg8 29. Ba2 Re5 30. Rf1 g5 31. f6 Rg6 32. Nh5 g4 33. hxg4 Rxg4 34. Qf3
Rgg5 35. Ng3 Rg6 36. Qe3 Qd7 37. Rf5 Rxf5 38. exf5 Rxf6 39. Nh5 Qxf5 40. Nxf6+
Qxf6 41. Bb1+ Kh8 42. Rf4 Qg7 43. Rg4 1-0

