66,97,82,94,75,145,145,118,105,101,111,105,103,103,85,96]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 {This is not going to be our chosen move order as
after ...e5, we reach different kinds of positions not covered in this camp.}
Nf6 6. c3 {However we transpose.} O-O 7. h3 e5 (7... d6 {as discussed this is
bad.} 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 a6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nc3 Rb8 12. Qc2 {Preparing to
develop the Bishop. Remmember we don't play b3 to do the exact same thing.} Qb6
13. Rb1 $1 {Once again it's better to not make this pawn move.} Nd7 14. Be3 {
White is well developed.}) (7... a6 8. Bxc6 bxc6 (8... dxc6 {also possible but
Black will lack central control.} 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 b6 11. Nc3 Bb7 12. Bf4 {
with central domination.}) 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 d5 11. e5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 Nxd2 13.
Bxd2 Qb6 14. b4 {fixing the c6-pawn, White's pawn is Bc3-Nd2-Nb3-Nc5 and game
over.}) 8. d3 d6 9. a3 Qc7 10. b4 b6 11. Nbd2 (11. Be3 {is the standard way,
but maybe White is improvising.} Bb7 12. Nbd2 a6 13. Bc4 b5 14. Bb3 {which
isn't as clear.}) 11... Bb7 12. Bb2 a5 $6 13. bxc5 bxc5 14. a4 Na7 15. Bc4 Rab8
16. Qc2 Bc6 17. Bc1 $1 Nc8 18. Bb3 Nb6 19. Nc4 Nxc4 20. Bxc4 Qb7 21. Bg5 Qb2
22. Qxb2 Rxb2 23. Reb1 Rxb1+ 24. Rxb1 Bxa4 25. Rb6 Bd1 26. Rxd6 Nh5 27. Be7 Re8
28. Rd7 a4 29. Bxc5 Bb3 30. Bxb3 axb3 31. Rb7 Nf4 32. Ne1 Ne2+ 33. Kf1 Nxc3 34.
Rxb3 Na4 35. Be3 Bf8 36. g3 Nc5 37. Rb5 Rc8 38. g4 h6 39. Ke2 Kg7 40. Nf3 f6
41. h4 Ne6 42. g5 hxg5 43. hxg5 Nxg5 44. Nxg5 fxg5 45. Rxe5 1-0

