{[%evp 0,69,21,26,48,51,48,41,41,37,37,19,8,4,4,2,17,17,23,-2,7,-1,-7,-13,8,7,
26,26,26,26,33,37,44,32,69,80,95,64,97,90,145,142,186,191,191,213,227,230,229,
242,242,255,268,266,266,232,231,330,284,284,284,294,288,291,314,322,322,336,
336,346,334,328] Navara David is an expert in this opening.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 e5 8. d3 {From now on, its
certain that both players are playing by plans.} d6 9. a3 (9. Be3 {It is
possible to play through this moveorder as well.} Qb6 10. Na3 a6 11. Ba4 {
note the b2-pawn is poisoned.}) 9... Qc7 (9... a6 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. b4 cxb4 12.
axb4 {White has a slight edge because of Black's weak structure.}) 10. b4 a6
11. Bc4 b6 12. Be3 Be6 (12... Bb7 {Black can also play this way.} 13. Nbd2 {
It's not clear what Black wants to do. While our plan is Rc1-d4.}) 13. Bxe6
fxe6 14. Nbd2 {All of a sudeen this is a good Italain for White.} h6 15. Qb3
Rfe8 16. Rac1 Kh7 17. d4 Nd7 18. Qa2 exd4 19. cxd4 Nd8 20. e5 Nb7 21. exd6 Qxd6
22. dxc5 bxc5 23. Ne4 Qd5 24. Qc2 Rac8 25. Red1 Qc6 26. Bxh6 Kxh6 27. Qd2+ Kh7
28. Qxd7 Qxd7 29. Rxd7 cxb4 30. Rxc8 Rxc8 31. axb4 Nd8 32. Nd6 Rb8 33. Ne8 Nf7
34. Nxg7 Kxg7 35. Ng5 1-0

