{[%evp 0,58,18,18,48,44,40,41,41,37,37,14,30,4,2,2,10,2,10,10,32,18,18,5,16,14,
-1,11,21,20,29,29,32,24,63,28,39,38,42,47,73,78,91,79,93,72,124,119,125,119,
120,98,107,54,115,141,240,220,260,332,260]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4.
O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 (5... a6 {Black is forcing, White to decide.} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7.
h3 Nf6 8. Re1 O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nd7 11. Nc3 e5 12. Be3 exd4 13. Bxd4 Bxd4
14. Qxd4 {White has active pieces while Black is struggling.}) (5... e6 {
planning some kind of Ne7-d5.} 6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 d5 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. e5 {
The next plan would be Nc3-Na4-b3-Ba3 and Nc5.}) 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 d5 8. e5 Ne8
9. d4 Qb6 10. Bxc6 $5 {The alternatives are possible too:} (10. Ba4) (10. Bf1)
10... bxc6 11. Nbd2 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc7 (12... c5 {Logical break but lacks
foundation.} 13. dxc5 Qxc5 14. Nb3 Qb5 15. Bg5 Qb7 16. Qd2 e6 17. Rac1 $14 {
Black's pieces lack activity.}) 13. Nb3 h6 (13... Ne6 14. Ng5 $1 {typical way
to get control of the c5-square.} Rb8 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Nc5 {followed by
b3-Ba3.}) 14. Nc5 Ne6 15. Na4 $3 {The point behind this amazing move is to
play b3-Ba3 and then and only then Nc5, to maintain our outpost.} Qb5 16. b3 $1
a5 17. Ba3 Ra7 18. g3 (18. Qd2 Bd7 19. Rac1 $16 {is also good enough. It
doesn't which continuation now.}) 18... Re8 19. Kg2 Nd8 20. Rc1 Qb8 21. Qd2 h5
22. Nc5 $16 Bf5 23. Nh4 Bc8 24. f4 Bh6 25. Rc3 Qc7 26. Qe2 Ne6 27. Nxe6 Bxe6
28. f5 gxf5 29. Rf1 Qd7 30. Qxh5 Bg7 31. Nxf5 Bxf5 32. Rxf5 Qe6 33. Rf4 Ra6 34.
Rg4 Kf8 35. Bc1 c5 36. Qh7 1-0

