1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. c3 Nf6 6. Re1 O-O 7. h3 Qb6 {
A serious try which is good.} 8. Ba4 (8. Bf1 {is also playable to avoid theory.
}) 8... d5 (8... Rd8 9. d3 $5 {which transistions into a middlegame where
plans matter. Some sample ideas would be:} d6 10. Nbd2 e5 11. a3 Qc7 12. b4 a6
13. Bb3 h6 14. Nf1 {followed by Ne3-Bb2 and so on.}) 9. e5 Nd7 10. d4 cxd4 11.
cxd4 Qd8 (11... e6 {supporting the pawn and stopping e6.} 12. Nc3 a6 13. Bxc6
Qxc6 (13... bxc6 14. Na4 Qb5 15. Be3 {with good control of the c5-square.}) 14.
Bg5 Re8 15. Qd2 Nb6 16. b3 Bd7 17. Rac1 {White is harmonious.}) 12. Nc3 Nb6 13.
Bxc6 $5 bxc6 14. b3 $1 f6 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Qd2 (16. e6 {The pawn on e6 blocks
Black further.} Rb8 17. h4 Na8 18. Na4 {typical manuever.} Nc7 19. Nc5 h5 20.
Nh2 f5 21. Nf3 {Black has no space and has lots of weaknesses.}) 16... Be6 17.
Ne2 g5 18. Nc1 g4 19. hxg4 Bxg4 20. Nh2 Bf5 21. Nd3 Bxd3 22. exf6 exf6 23. Qxd3
Qd7 24. Nf1 Rxe1 25. Rxe1 Re8 26. Rxe8+ Qxe8 27. Qa6 Qd7 28. Bc5 Nc8 29. Ng3
Kf7 30. Qd3 Kg8 31. Nf5 Qe8 32. Qa6 Qd8 33. Qxc8 1-0

