c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. O-O Bg7 5. Re1 Nf6 6. c3 O-O 7. h3 d6 8. d4 cxd4 9.
cxd4 a6 (9... d5 10. e5 Ne4 11. Bxc6 {creating a weakness.} bxc6 12. Be3 Rb8
13. Qc1 {White has actually won a tempo as in usual lines, because Black
played d6-d5.}) 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Nc3 {knights before bishops.} Bb7 (11... Rb8
12. Qc2 {intending to develop the Bishop on f4. Once again, we don't play
moves like b3 for the same purpose.}) 12. Bg5 (12. Bf4 {I usually prefer this.}
) 12... h6 (12... Nd7 13. Qd2 {usual way for stabalizing the Bishop.}) 13. Bf4
c5 14. d5 $1 (14. dxc5 $5 dxc5 15. Be5 {An important move, we deprive Black
with his advantage of the pair Bishops as he will one day move the knight.})
14... Nd7 15. Qd2 g5 (15... Kh7 16. Rad1 {preparing e5, simple chess.}) 16. Bg3
f5 17. exf5 Rxf5 18. Qd3 $1 Rf7 19. Re3 Qf8 20. Rae1 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Qg7 22. c4
Nf8 23. Qb3 Bc8 24. Qb6 Ng6 25. Qc6 Rb8 26. Rb3 Rxb3 27. Qxc8+ Kh7 28. axb3 Qc3
29. Qe6 Kg7 30. Qe3 Qb2 31. h4 g4 32. h5 gxf3 33. hxg6 Kxg6 34. gxf3 Kh7 35.
Kg2 Rg7 36. Qd3+ 1-0

